time, you lose 90% of them.

00:10:02.950 --> 00:10:04.500
And to me, this is
a great case where

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:05.960
you could lose 90% of them.

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:08.260
So you then select that
when the user is very nice.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:09.950
And they say, OK, yes I will.

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:12.440
And then they get this, oh,
you got to give me permission.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.530
And then they say OK to that.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:17.210
And then it's like OK, once
they've given permission,

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:19.170
now I have to ask for
the contacts again.

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:21.680
Once they give that
permission, now finally,

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:25.297
oh, what account do you
want to sign in with?

00:10:25.297 --> 00:10:26.880
This phone only has
one account on it,

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:28.580
but yet you need to tell
me the account that you're

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:29.740
going to sign in with.

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:30.700
So that's what?

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:32.300
That's the fifth from the left.

00:10:32.300 --> 00:10:35.720
So once they pick that one, and
they sign in, now guess what?

00:10:35.720 --> 00:10:37.690
This user didn't have
a Google+ profile.

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:38.970
Oh, we can't continue.

00:10:38.970 --> 00:10:40.780
We need to fill out
a Google+ profile.

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:43.300
So they would have to fill
out a Google+ profile.

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:46.730
They create that, submit,
and then finally, guess what?

00:10:46.730 --> 00:10:48.370
It's asking them for
their basic info,

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:50.560
including the list
of their contacts.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:51.840
And then they say, OK to that.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:52.450
They allow it.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:55.100
And then finally, they're
signed into the application.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:56.470
There's a lot of friction here.

00:10:56.470 --> 00:10:57.512
We understand this.

00:10:57.512 --> 00:10:58.720
So we've tried to improve it.

00:10:58.720 --> 00:10:59.600
And we fixed it.

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:01.470
So now it looks like this.

00:11:01.470 --> 00:11:04.420
So now we say, OK,
let's get started.

00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:05.816
Let's sign in with Google.

00:11:05.816 --> 00:11:07.190
The first thing
is, well, we just

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:08.530
need to know which
account on your phone

00:11:08.530 --> 00:11:09.607
you're signing in with.

00:11:09.607 --> 00:11:11.440
In this case, I'm going
to pick the account.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:15.470
And then in most cases,
I'm straight into the app.

00:11:15.470 --> 00:11:17.170
Sometimes, there
will be another step

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:18.970
between the second
and third of these,

00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:21.890
and that's if the user has
to give specific permissions

00:11:21.890 --> 00:11:22.780
to access something.

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.790
I like to use Google
Drive as an example.

00:11:24.790 --> 00:11:26.498
So if you're building
an application that

00:11:26.498 --> 00:11:28.420
accesses their stuff
on Google Drive,

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:32.090
then they would have a third
step in between the middle one

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:33.340
and the one on the right here.

00:11:33.340 --> 00:11:35.162
But that's how
frictionless it has become.

00:11:35.162 --> 00:11:36.620
We're really, really
proud of this.

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:39.078
We shipped this in the last
version of Google Play Services

00:11:39.078 --> 00:11:40.560
back in September-ish.

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:43.650
And we think it will make it
a lot easier for your users

00:11:43.650 --> 00:11:46.400
to be able to sign in, and to be
able to feel secure in signing

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:48.760
in without all these
dialogues asking them

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:50.750
for stuff-- sometimes
stuff that may not

00:11:50.750 --> 00:11:54.200
be actually relevant to what
they're doing right now.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.319
So the next part is I
spoke about security.

00:11:57.319 --> 00:11:58.860
And one of the
points-- so we've made

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:00.270
it easier for your end users.

00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:01.630
And now we want to
talk about security.

00:12:01.630 --> 00:12:03.210
And I think it's really
important in security

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:04.690
that security isn't
a static thing.

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:06.526
Security is always
a moving target.

00:12:06.526 --> 00:12:07.900
And it's really,
really important

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:09.140
to stay ahead of the game.

00:12:09.140 --> 00:12:11.500
And part of our job at
Google is to stay ahead

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.350
of the game in the
security landscape.

00:12:13.350 --> 00:12:15.100
I like to show this infographic.

00:12:15.100 --> 00:12:18.584
So this is from a website called
informationisbeautiful.net.

00:12:18.584 --> 00:12:19.500
There's a public link.

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:20.410
I have it in my slides.

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:22.880
If anybody wants the slides, I
can share the link out later.

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:24.796
Or if you fill out that
form, and just ask me,

00:12:24.796 --> 00:12:26.630
I'll send the link to you.

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:28.670
Now look at all
of these breaches.

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:31.890
And look at all of the users
that were impacted by that.

00:12:31.890 --> 00:12:35.000
Some of these are in the
tens of millions of users

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.080
that were affected by a breach.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:39.610
Some of these we might
be familiar with.

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:42.040
Probably the most
famous one recently

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.870
was the Ashley Madison
one where 36 million users

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:48.590
had very, very personal data
leaked onto the internet.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:52.150
And then some banks, and
stores, and that kind of thing

00:12:52.150 --> 00:12:55.499
where people had personal
information leaked out-- maybe

00:12:55.499 --> 00:12:58.040
not onto the internet, like in
the case of the Ashley Madison

00:12:58.040 --> 00:12:58.690
one.

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:01.730
But the overall picture
that people have

00:13:01.730 --> 00:13:05.540
is that their data, their
personal details, their credit

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:07.910
card, other stuff
like that, is at risk

00:13:07.910 --> 00:13:09.770
every single day from hackers.

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:12.710
Now a lot of this stuff,
of course, was inside jobs.

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:14.280
Some of the retail
ones where people

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:17.442
had planted a worm inside the
credit card scanning machines

00:13:17.442 --> 00:13:19.650
that was able to collect
data about credit cards that

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:20.862
were scanned.

00:13:20.862 --> 00:13:22.570
It's a little bit of
a different scenario

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:23.770
than you may be
facing when you're

00:13:23.770 --> 00:13:25.210
building something for sign-in.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:28.230
But the bottom line is to
users, it's all the same.

00:13:28.230 --> 00:13:30.910
It's really, really a
feeling of insecurity

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:32.560
that people are out
there to get them.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:34.372
And it's our job to
at least try to help

00:13:34.372 --> 00:13:36.330
them feel a little bit
more secure when they're

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:38.160
using your apps,
when they're using

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:40.720
your sites, that kind of thing.

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:43.200
So you don't want
to be this guy.

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:45.600
And you want to help
them not to be this guy.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:48.020
Sometimes I think I should
just change my passwords

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.270
and correct for this reason.

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:52.460
We really want to help
them not be this guy.

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:55.040
So the next part that I want
to talk about a little bit

00:13:55.040 --> 00:13:58.350
is one of the biggest things
where your users are at risk,

00:13:58.350 --> 00:14:00.276
and that's from phishing scams.

00:14:00.276 --> 00:14:01.650
Now, there was
some research done

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:04.070
by the Canadian government.

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:11.300
And this research found that
156 million phishing emails

00:14:11.300 --> 00:14:13.707
are sent out every single day.

00:14:13.707 --> 00:14:16.290
Now, by the way, this research
was done a couple of years ago.

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:18.500
So I think these numbers
are probably bigger now.

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:22.070
So of those 156 million phishing
e-mails-- now of course,

00:14:22.070 --> 00:14:24.690
we all have great
e-mail filters.

00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:28.370
We all have great tools
that allow us to filter out,

00:14:28.370 --> 00:14:31.290
and to stop phishing
scams, and to block them.

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:34.010
So how many of that
156 million do you

00:14:34.010 --> 00:14:35.860
think got through these filters?

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:39.120
Anybody take a guess?

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:41.250
Did somebody say 10%?

00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:42.490
That's a good guess.

00:14:42.490 --> 00:14:46.590
16 million, around 10%,
actually got through.

00:14:46.590 --> 00:14:49.640
So when you think
about this, a lot

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:52.500
of the free e-mail providers,
like Gmail, and Yahoo,

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:55.600
and Hotmail, et cetera, they
all provide these spam filters.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:57.520
And I'm sure like
many of you, I've

00:14:57.520 --> 00:14:59.196
gotten my name on all of them.

00:14:59.196 --> 00:15:01.862
I'm lmoroney@yahoo,
@hotmail, @gmail,

00:15:01.862 --> 00:15:03.070
and all these kind of things.

00:15:03.070 --> 00:15:06.540
And these try their best to
keep spam and phishing away

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:08.464
from my eyes.

00:15:08.464 --> 00:15:09.630
Some are better than others.

00:15:09.630 --> 00:15:11.327
I won't say which are bad.

00:15:11.327 --> 00:15:13.660
But most of them try to keep
phishing away from my eyes.

00:15:13.660 --> 00:15:15.060
But some of them do get through.

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:17.750
But it's a little bit of
a side benefit, I think,

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:20.640
if you're using
something like a Gmail

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:25.620
because these services
receive the most phishing.

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:28.720
They're best at identifying
phishing-- much more than maybe

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:30.454
an independent server would be.

00:15:30.454 --> 00:15:32.870
And as a result, if your users
are already using something

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:34.650
like Gmail, then
they're already being

00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:37.000
less exposed to phishing
scams because less

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.209
are reaching their inbox.

00:15:38.209 --> 00:15:39.750
I don't know about
you who use Gmail,

00:15:39.750 --> 00:15:41.440
but I think when
I look at phishing

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:43.870
e-mails that are sent
to me, far less than 10%

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:46.000
get to my Gmail inbox.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:46.720
All right.

00:15:46.720 --> 00:15:50.870
So 16 million of the 156
million got through filters

00:15:50.870 --> 00:15:52.050
to end users.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:54.020
How many of those
16 million do you

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:58.130
think were actually
opened by the end users?

00:15:58.130 --> 00:16:00.050
A quarter of a million?

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:01.080
OK.

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:04.190
It's higher than
quarter of a million.

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:05.780
Sorry?

00:16:05.780 --> 00:16:06.860
25%?

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:10.110
OK, it's actually
higher than 25%.

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:14.120
I feel like a game
show here, right?

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:14.700
80%?

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:17.840
It's lower than 80%.

00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:18.640
50%.

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:19.810
Thank you.

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:22.360
It's actually eight
million-- about half.

00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:25.910
Now remember, this is every
single day users are opening--

00:16:25.910 --> 00:16:27.240
and this was an older research.

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:28.730
I think it's
probably higher now.

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:30.260
Every single day,
users were found

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:33.260
to be opening eight
million phishing scams.

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:34.380
OK, next question.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:37.380
Most phishing scams have
a link in them, right?

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:40.040
The typical phishing
scam is like, oh, I'm

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:42.170
from-- insert your
mail service here--

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:44.060
Your password has failed.

00:16:44.060 --> 00:16:46.340
Please sign in here to
change your password.

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:47.410
That's the typical one.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:48.826
So there's usually
a link that you

00:16:48.826 --> 00:16:51.950
go to, to a fake website, where
they harvest your password.

00:16:51.950 --> 00:16:54.380
So how many of
those eight million

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:56.820
do you think the people
actually clicked on the link

00:16:56.820 --> 00:17:00.050
and went to the website?

00:17:00.050 --> 00:17:00.630
A million.

00:17:00.630 --> 00:17:01.630
OK, that's close enough.

00:17:01.630 --> 00:17:02.560
It's 10%.

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:04.220
It's about 800,000.

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:09.380
So every single day, 800,000
of these links are clicked on.

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:12.640
And people are going to sites
with phishing scams on them.

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:13.550
All right.

00:17:13.550 --> 00:17:14.660
You go to this site.

00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:17.270
Now, a lot of the time you've
gone to this site-- and most

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:19.228
people in this room, I'm
sure, are smart enough

00:17:19.228 --> 00:17:22.050
to look at the URL and see
that, hey look, this URL isn't

00:17:22.050 --> 00:17:24.720
yahoo.com or google.com,
or wherever, Facebook,

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:26.079
or wherever.

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:29.670
It's bob.biz slash something.

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:32.275
And nowadays, browsers have
that like little green thing

00:17:32.275 --> 00:17:34.650
that they put in the address
bar to show that this really

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:37.070
is certified, that this
is the correct site.

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:40.150
But 800,000 of these people
have gone to these sites.

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:42.310
How many of them do you
think were still fooled

00:17:42.310 --> 00:17:45.650
and actually entered
their user data?

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:46.390
Half?

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:48.550
OK, thank God it's a
bit less than that.

00:17:48.550 --> 00:17:50.100
It's still 10%.

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:51.460
It's about 80,000.

00:17:51.460 --> 00:17:55.700
So per day, 80,000 people
fall for a phishing scam.

00:17:55.700 --> 00:17:58.440
And many of those usernames
and passwords are compromised.

00:17:58.440 --> 00:18:00.330
People might be using
the same username

00:18:00.330 --> 00:18:02.230
and password on other sites.

00:18:02.230 --> 00:18:04.400
Like I said, for me,
there is a phrase

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:06.210
that I know that
nobody else knows.

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:08.590
And most of my passwords
kind of root off

00:18:08.590 --> 00:18:11.230
of that phrase by changing
letters around, or adding

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:12.770
numbers, or punctuation.

00:18:12.770 --> 00:18:14.530
And it helps me to
remember passwords.

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:17.112
So had I gone to one of
these phishing sites,

00:18:17.112 --> 00:18:19.320
and if any of phishers are
watching this live stream,

00:18:19.320 --> 00:18:21.820
they now know that my password
has that kind of combination.

00:18:21.820 --> 00:18:23.450
So maybe I need to change it.

00:18:23.450 --> 00:18:26.660
But if they've gotten one of
these sources of my password,

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:28.900
then they already
have several steps

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:32.060
towards being able to compromise
my account in other places.

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:35.060
So it's a tough
landscape out there.

00:18:35.060 --> 00:18:36.820
And it's up to us
as app developers

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:40.880
and as site developers to
protect our end users in that.

00:18:40.880 --> 00:18:43.190
So as part of the
values that we try

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:46.340
to offer with Google Sign-In,
all of this kind of stuff

00:18:46.340 --> 00:18:47.460
becomes possible.

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:51.410
So when you use a Gmail sign-in,
when you use a Google account,

00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:53.790
I'm sure a lot of you, like
me, travel around-- maybe

00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:55.710
around the country,
maybe around the world.

00:18:55.710 --> 00:18:57.920
You've probably
encountered these things.

00:18:57.920 --> 00:19:01.160
I was in England two weeks ago.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:03.460
And when I tried to
sign in in England,

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:05.310
Google didn't challenge me.

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:07.810
I then the following
day went to Wales.

00:19:07.810 --> 00:19:09.690
And when I tried to
sign in from Wales,

00:19:09.690 --> 00:19:12.136
Google were like, this
is suspicious activity.

00:19:12.136 --> 00:19:14.260
We're going to challenge
you for some extra details

00:19:14.260 --> 00:19:17.136
just to make sure that you
really are moving around.

00:19:17.136 --> 00:19:19.010
You've been in three
countries in three days.

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:20.450
What's really going on here?

00:19:20.450 --> 00:19:22.190
And it was an extra
layer of security

00:19:22.190 --> 00:19:25.020
that Google were able to provide
to protect my password in case

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:27.200
somebody really was
scamming me, somebody really

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:28.900
was taking that kind of thing.

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:30.940
Another tool that's
in there is being

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:32.854
able to sign out of
sessions remotely.

00:19:32.854 --> 00:19:34.270
Now, one of the
things that's nice

00:19:34.270 --> 00:19:37.280
is that if you use internet
cafes, or that kind of thing,

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:39.570
and you sign into your Gmail,
and you forget about it,

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:41.550
you can go, and you
can sign out remotely.

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:43.520
But it's also really
nice that, hey, you've

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:45.190
gotten this warning.

00:19:45.190 --> 00:19:47.490
We've detected suspicious
activity on your account.

00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:50.020
Somebody in Wales has tried
to sign into your account.

00:19:50.020 --> 00:19:51.031
What's going on here?

00:19:51.031 --> 00:19:53.280
You can then go and just
kick that person out remotely

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:57.110
before you change
your password details.

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:58.110
Things like that.

00:19:58.110 --> 00:20:00.510
Unusual activity alerts--
same kind of thing.

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:02.730
If there's strange activity
going on, you get alerts.

00:20:02.730 --> 00:20:04.005
You get alerts sent to you.

00:20:04.005 --> 00:20:06.580
You can have alerts details
and all that texted to you,

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:07.480
and whatever.

00:20:07.480 --> 00:20:09.050
There's some
intelligent challenges

00:20:09.050 --> 00:20:10.430
on there for the same reason.

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:13.090
There's all of this
infrastructure designed

00:20:13.090 --> 00:20:15.830
to protect your
username and password.

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:19.870
So if you were one of these
people who inadvertently gave

00:20:19.870 --> 00:20:21.600
some details out
in a phishing scam,

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:24.840
you can find out right
away when your users,

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:29.206
or when you are using
a Google identity.

00:20:29.206 --> 00:20:30.830
And then there's all
the infrastructure

00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:32.580
that I mentioned behind
it, all the security

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:33.496
of the infrastructure.

00:20:33.496 --> 00:20:35.950
One of the main places that
passwords get compromised

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:37.700
is that somewhere
in a system, they're

00:20:37.700 --> 00:20:39.580
stored in a place
that's unencrypted.

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:41.550
Or maybe they're
passing from A to B

00:20:41.550 --> 00:20:43.490
across an infrastructure
that's unencrypted.

00:20:43.490 --> 00:20:46.150
And it's easy for somebody
to sniff that off a network.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:48.420
And as a result, passwords
can be compromised.

00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:51.740
Again, the infrastructure that's
behind Google's credential

00:20:51.740 --> 00:20:54.189
system, behind our
ID system, hopefully

00:20:54.189 --> 00:20:55.230
doesn't have any of that.

00:20:55.230 --> 00:20:57.400
We haven't had any--
at least that I

00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:59.460
know of right now-- any
major compromises or that

00:20:59.460 --> 00:21:00.043
kind of thing.

00:21:00.043 --> 00:21:03.090
So again, if your users
are using Google Identity,

00:21:03.090 --> 00:21:05.490
if they're using any kind
of Sign-In with Google,

00:21:05.490 --> 00:21:08.130
all of this backend
is there for them.

00:21:08.130 --> 00:21:09.620
So enough about the user.

00:21:09.620 --> 00:21:11.350
What about the developer story?

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:14.270
And I mentioned earlier on about
there were some difficulties.

00:21:14.270 --> 00:21:16.600
And there were some bumps
in the road that you have

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:17.840
when you try to sign in.

00:21:17.840 --> 00:21:19.510
So we've tried to
make it a lot easier.

00:21:19.510 --> 00:21:21.960
And I'm going to talk through
some of the steps here.

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:24.660
I'm not going to demo it because
unfortunately, the emulator

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:27.590
doesn't yet run the version
of Google Play Services that

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:28.460
has this on it.

00:21:28.460 --> 00:21:30.793
And it's just too awkward to
try and do it with a device

00:21:30.793 --> 00:21:31.630
while I'm on stage.

00:21:31.630 --> 00:21:33.800
So I'm just going to
demo by showing the code.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:36.440
So first step-- instead
of connecting directly

00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:39.950
to Google API Client, the API
has this thing called a Google

00:21:39.950 --> 00:21:41.280
Sign-In Options Object.

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:43.700
Or we just call it
a GSO for short.

00:21:43.700 --> 00:21:46.640
So your first task
is to create a GSO.

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:49.020
And in this case, I'm
doing a very simple one.

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:51.490
I'm not requesting any
additional permissions other

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:53.380
than the basic email identifier.

00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:55.490
And thinking about just
the person's email address

00:21:55.490 --> 00:21:57.650
as the thing that they
identify themselves with,

00:21:57.650 --> 00:21:59.610
you saw that dialog
earlier with the pop-up

00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:02.460
where it was like [INAUDIBLE]
and his email address.

00:22:02.460 --> 00:22:04.040
That's what springs this.

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:06.730
And this doesn't require any
permissions from the user other

00:22:06.730 --> 00:22:08.700
than just filling in
that account picker.

00:22:08.700 --> 00:22:10.910
If you were, for example,
to access Google Drive,

00:22:10.910 --> 00:22:13.740
or you wanted to access Google
Drive, or any other things,

00:22:13.740 --> 00:22:16.969
there would be an additional
dot on here before the .build.

00:22:16.969 --> 00:22:19.510
And then the user would get the
dialog saying, hey, you know,

00:22:19.510 --> 00:22:22.114
this app also wants to access
to Google Drive, et cetera.

00:22:22.114 --> 00:22:23.530
But if you're doing
this, and this

00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:25.897
is the basic and the
most common case,

00:22:25.897 --> 00:22:27.980
you're just going to have
those three steps that I

00:22:27.980 --> 00:22:30.500
showed in the earlier slide.

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:33.300
Next now, if you have built
with Google Play Services,

00:22:33.300 --> 00:22:36.040
and if you've built with
authentication and Identity

00:22:36.040 --> 00:22:37.580
with Google Play
Services, you'll

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:39.320
know about the
Google API client.

00:22:39.320 --> 00:22:41.670
And here's where you set
up the Google API client.

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:43.180
You create it with a builder.

00:22:43.180 --> 00:22:45.860
And you access it with the @API.

00:22:45.860 --> 00:22:47.820
And you pass it the
GSO that you just

00:22:47.820 --> 00:22:50.080
created earlier on the
second parameter there.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:52.310
It's off the Google Sign-In API.

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:54.060
And you just pass
it that GSO object.

00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:56.190
And that GSO object
had the configurations

00:22:56.190 --> 00:22:59.070
for the type of permissions
that you want to access.

00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:00.364
So it's as simple as that.

00:23:00.364 --> 00:23:02.530
The function to determine
if there's an auth class--

00:23:02.530 --> 00:23:03.696
there's a constant on there.

00:23:03.696 --> 00:23:06.000
And that constant is
the Google Sign-In API.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.030
So now you've created a GSO.

00:23:08.030 --> 00:23:10.250
You've created your
Google API client.

00:23:10.250 --> 00:23:13.070
So the next thing to do
is to get a sign-in intent

00:23:13.070 --> 00:23:15.507
from the API for this
Google API client.

00:23:15.507 --> 00:23:16.590
And you can see it's here.

00:23:16.590 --> 00:23:18.820
I just create intent--
.signin.Intent--

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:21.390
equals of the
Google Sign-In API.

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:23.350
I pass it the API clients.

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:25.030
Remember the API
client was configured

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:26.360
with the sign-in object.

00:23:26.360 --> 00:23:28.980
And then I start an
activity for that result.

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:30.480
There's a constant
on the right hand

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:33.770
side there-- [? rcSignin. ?]
That's not part of the API.

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:35.750
Usually, if you're
building an application,

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.630
and you start an
activity, so that Android

00:23:38.630 --> 00:23:42.140
can tell which activity
result is for which activity,

00:23:42.140 --> 00:23:43.549
you just pass it an integer.

00:23:43.549 --> 00:23:45.090
And it can be anything
that you want.

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:46.240
It's just up to you.

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:48.300
If you've got multiple
activities going on,

00:23:48.300 --> 00:23:51.160
it's up to you to identify
them with your own constants.

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:53.500
So in this case, this
constant, [? rcSignin, ?]

00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:54.515
I think we've made it.

00:23:54.515 --> 00:23:56.140
There is a sample
that you can download

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:57.264
that I took this code from.

00:23:57.264 --> 00:23:58.760
I think was like 7,001.

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:00.440
So when you get the
callback saying,

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:02.559
hey, we got a result
for activity 7,001,

00:24:02.559 --> 00:24:04.850
you know that it's that one,
that it's the sign-in one.

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:07.817
But like I said, it can
be anything you like.

00:24:07.817 --> 00:24:09.400
And then you can see
the callback here

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:12.600
where you catch the
activity results.

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:14.360
So you get your own
activity results.

00:24:14.360 --> 00:24:16.300
And then on the
activity results,

00:24:16.300 --> 00:24:17.496
you have a request code.

00:24:17.496 --> 00:24:19.870
Remember the request code that
I said that you passed in.

00:24:19.870 --> 00:24:21.660
If it's that request
code that you created

00:24:21.660 --> 00:24:24.230
for the sign-in activity,
then all you have to do

00:24:24.230 --> 00:24:27.250
is create a Google
Sign-In result object.

00:24:27.250 --> 00:24:30.780
And this is going to be the
result of the call to Google

00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:33.910
Sign-In API, .getSignin
result from the intent.

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:36.020
And the intent passes you
back the data parameter

00:24:36.020 --> 00:24:37.460
that you can see at the top.

00:24:37.460 --> 00:24:39.040
So now you have your
sign-in results.

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:41.180
And this sign-in result
object gives you everything

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:44.550
that you need to know about the
sign-in, such as the account.

00:24:44.550 --> 00:24:47.650
And the account is a Google
Sign-In account object.

00:24:47.650 --> 00:24:50.410
And you get that using the
result .getSigninAccount,

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:52.160
as it suggests.

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.410
And then you can query that
account object for things

00:24:54.410 --> 00:24:56.827
that the user has given you
permission to, including, hey,

00:24:56.827 --> 00:24:58.534
has this user actually
signed in and out?

00:24:58.534 --> 00:24:59.480
That kind of thing.

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:01.390
So now that you have
your accounts, now

00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:04.060
you can personalize your
application for that end user.

00:25:04.060 --> 00:25:05.630
And it's as simple as that.

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:08.590
And again, just to look at the
flow again, it looks like this.

00:25:08.590 --> 00:25:11.100
The user clicks the
Connect with Google button.

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:14.070
They get given the picker,
which asks them which accounts

00:25:14.070 --> 00:25:15.420
do they want to sign in with.

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:16.530
They pick that account.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:18.400
And then they're taken
to your application.

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:19.983
And you can customize
your application

00:25:19.983 --> 00:25:21.986
as you please for that user.

00:25:21.986 --> 00:25:23.360
Like in this case,
we see we have

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:25.150
the user's name, and
a picture, and stuff

00:25:25.150 --> 00:25:26.470
at the top for that user.

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:28.178
And as I mentioned
before, that if you're

00:25:28.178 --> 00:25:30.600
doing additional
scopes-- for example,

00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:32.240
the one I always like
to use is Drive--

00:25:32.240 --> 00:25:34.448
that if your app is going
to access the user's Drive,

00:25:34.448 --> 00:25:37.087
there'll be an additional
step in between the middle one

00:25:37.087 --> 00:25:38.670
and the right one
there where the user

00:25:38.670 --> 00:25:41.530
has to give permission to that.

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:42.610
So this is great.

00:25:42.610 --> 00:25:43.940
But guess what.

00:25:43.940 --> 00:25:46.612
This is all very nice for
authenticating on the device.

00:25:46.612 --> 00:25:48.820
But what happens when you
want to extend beyond that?

00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:51.030
And I like to give a story here.

00:25:51.030 --> 00:25:53.950
Before I joined Google, I was
an independent application

00:25:53.950 --> 00:25:54.640
developer.

00:25:54.640 --> 00:25:57.716
I worked for a lot of startups,
building applications for them.

00:25:57.716 --> 00:25:59.340
And there was one
startup that I worked

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:02.580
with that they had this really
interesting app for a very

00:26:02.580 --> 00:26:04.240
unique audience.

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:07.100
And their audience
was people who

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:11.340
own pets who hire other people
to look after their pets

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:12.360
for them.

00:26:12.360 --> 00:26:16.520
So part of this was
like, I have a dog.

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:17.750
I'll use my own dog.

00:26:17.750 --> 00:26:19.200
My dog is called Bucky.

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:23.320
And if I, for example, work too
much, and I can't walk Bucky,

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:25.840
then I can hire somebody
to walk Bucky for me.

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:27.840
But how do I know that
that person has actually

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:29.640
walked my dog for me?

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:31.550
So the idea behind
this app was that I

00:26:31.550 --> 00:26:34.680
would have this person
they've hired use this app.

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:37.030
So then as they're looking
after my dog during the day,

00:26:37.030 --> 00:26:39.613
as they're walking the dog, it
would collect data around that.

00:26:39.613 --> 00:26:41.580
It would collect data
of where they walked,

00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:42.704
and all that kind of stuff.

00:26:42.704 --> 00:26:44.520
It was an interesting
little concept.

00:26:44.520 --> 00:26:46.550
But of course, in order
to be able to use this,

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:50.310
people needed to sign
up for this service.

00:26:50.310 --> 00:26:52.510
They register that
I am who I am.

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:54.320
And here's my password
that I sign in.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:57.320
And I add dog walkers
to my account.

00:26:57.320 --> 00:26:59.590
And so first of all, we
hit the first barriers

00:26:59.590 --> 00:27:02.050
that I was talking about earlier
on of yet another sign-up

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:03.100
that people had to do.

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:05.020
So we thought, OK,
let's add social.

00:27:05.020 --> 00:27:06.620
Let's add Sign-In with Google.

00:27:06.620 --> 00:27:08.370
Lets add sign in with Facebook.

00:27:08.370 --> 00:27:10.000
Lets add sign in
with Yahoo, and sign

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.458
in with Microsoft, and all
these kind of things in the app.

00:27:12.458 --> 00:27:14.460
So it makes it easier for
people to get into it.

00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:17.010
So that was the first part,
and it was all very nice.

00:27:17.010 --> 00:27:20.640
But then we had all this backend
data, the backend example

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:22.460
including the address
of the person who

00:27:22.460 --> 00:27:26.082
owns the dog, the site
where the dog gets walked,

00:27:26.082 --> 00:27:27.040
all this kind of stuff.

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:29.660
And it's like, OK, it's
not crazy sensitive data,

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:33.080
such as bank account
details, or other stuff that

00:27:33.080 --> 00:27:35.530
has been leaked on the
internet in the recent past.

00:27:35.530 --> 00:27:38.270
But it's potentially sensitive.

00:27:38.270 --> 00:27:39.580
People know where I live.

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:41.810
Maybe I have a really
expensive breed of dog

00:27:41.810 --> 00:27:43.360
that could be kidnapped.

00:27:43.360 --> 00:27:44.106
Who knows?

00:27:44.106 --> 00:27:45.480
So there is
sensitive data there.

00:27:45.480 --> 00:27:47.640
So how do we secure
that backend data?

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:50.840
And it's all very nice that if
we had a Sign-In with Google

00:27:50.840 --> 00:27:52.870
that gets people
into my application

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:54.290
locally on my device.

00:27:54.290 --> 00:27:56.030
And I can customize it for them.

00:27:56.030 --> 00:27:58.270
But what then if those
credentials get passed up

00:27:58.270 --> 00:28:00.370
to my backend
server, and I start

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:02.740
needing to identify the
person on the backend server?

00:28:02.740 --> 00:28:05.760
Now suddenly, you can have a
middleman coming in, and maybe

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:08.370
a middleman posting stuff
to my server, saying,

00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:10.130
yes this is Laurence Moroney.

00:28:10.130 --> 00:28:12.230
It's lmoroney@gmail.com.

00:28:12.230 --> 00:28:14.250
Give me his details.

00:28:14.250 --> 00:28:17.440
So we need to be really
careful about extending

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:19.330
our applications to handle that.

00:28:19.330 --> 00:28:20.570
So here's an example.

00:28:20.570 --> 00:28:22.026
Here's my app.

00:28:22.026 --> 00:28:22.900
My app has signed in.

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:24.390
By the way, do you
love my diagrams?

00:28:24.390 --> 00:28:26.306
I'm not the most artistic
person in the world.

00:28:26.306 --> 00:28:29.140
So my app has a
Sign-In with Google.

00:28:29.140 --> 00:28:31.820
Google has provided an
identity for my user.

00:28:31.820 --> 00:28:33.420
And maybe I'm
keying that identity

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:35.070
off the user's email address.

00:28:35.070 --> 00:28:37.630
I then pass that e-mail
address up to my server.

00:28:37.630 --> 00:28:39.770
And what can happen is
the bad guys can say,

00:28:39.770 --> 00:28:43.280
huh, I can pass an e-mail
to the server as well.

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:44.880
And then what happens?

00:28:44.880 --> 00:28:47.770
If I pass the email
to the server as well,

00:28:47.770 --> 00:28:49.320
the server might be
able to post back

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:51.660
to me some of the details
about this person.

00:28:51.660 --> 00:28:53.380
That would be bad.

00:28:53.380 --> 00:28:55.750
So part of the extensibility
of Sign-In with Google

00:28:55.750 --> 00:28:58.390
that we've done is say, OK,
let's treat this a little bit

00:28:58.390 --> 00:29:00.380
differently.

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:02.760
My application, as well as
being able to sign in and get

00:29:02.760 --> 00:29:05.070
an identity from the
user, such as their email,

00:29:05.070 --> 00:29:06.820
I can also get this token.

00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:09.820
And this token says,
OK, lmoroney@gmail.com

00:29:09.820 --> 00:29:10.910
has signed in.

00:29:10.910 --> 00:29:12.250
He signed in at this time.

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:14.150
Here's some of the
metadata around that.

00:29:14.150 --> 00:29:15.510
Here's how we're signing that.

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:17.940
Here's how we're encrypting
and securing that.

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:21.190
My app can pass that
token up to my server.

00:29:21.190 --> 00:29:24.070
So now the server passes
that token to Google

00:29:24.070 --> 00:29:26.400
and gets an ACK back
saying, yes, this is good.

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:29.160
Or this really is a
token that we issued.

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:31.540
This really is
lmoroney@gmail.com.

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:33.250
This isn't some kind of fake.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:34.940
This is the person.

00:29:34.940 --> 00:29:37.680
Now, how we can do
this-- there's two ways.

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:40.126
The way that we recommend is
we've got a set of libraries

00:29:40.126 --> 00:29:41.000
that you can do this.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.390
So those libraries do that
communication on your behalf.

00:29:43.390 --> 00:29:45.080
And I have a few code
snippets I'll show

00:29:45.080 --> 00:29:46.205
in a moment that show them.

00:29:46.205 --> 00:29:48.342
But we also have an
endpoints that you can call.

00:29:48.342 --> 00:29:50.800
Then you can just call that
endpoint and get the data back.

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:52.830
We recommend the
endpoint for debugging.

00:29:52.830 --> 00:29:53.980
And it's all in the docs.

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:56.330
I have some links at
the end of the slide.

00:29:56.330 --> 00:29:58.740
But we recommend the
libraries for production work.

