00:32:36.550 --> 00:32:39.680
is that token that's come
from your Android client,

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:42.840
has been posted to the server
just as a string on an http

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:46.180
post, or hopefully in an https
post-- your secure post--

00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:47.557
and you get your ID token.

00:32:47.557 --> 00:32:48.640
So you want to just check.

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.610
If it's not null, now
you have this on the API.

00:32:52.610 --> 00:32:54.570
This is not part
of the Android API.

00:32:54.570 --> 00:32:56.520
This is part of the
libraries that I mentioned

00:32:56.520 --> 00:32:59.030
that you can use on your
backend server, the Google

00:32:59.030 --> 00:33:00.960
Libraries for authentication.

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:02.720
An object in there
is called-- surprise,

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:05.780
surprise-- a Google
ID token verifier.

00:33:05.780 --> 00:33:07.810
The Google ID token
verifier is then

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:09.750
built just using a
couple of objects

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:11.162
to transport in the JsonFactory.

00:33:11.162 --> 00:33:13.620
But the important thing is,
two things that you need to do.

00:33:13.620 --> 00:33:15.700
Number one, you need
to set the audience.

00:33:15.700 --> 00:33:19.846
Now, the audience can be a
number of different servers

00:33:19.846 --> 00:33:21.720
because you may have
multiple servers posting

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:22.330
into this thing.

00:33:22.330 --> 00:33:24.163
And you want the audience
for each of these.

00:33:24.163 --> 00:33:25.600
In the scenario,
I just have one.

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:26.990
And the ID for that--
if you remember,

00:33:26.990 --> 00:33:29.010
I was talking earlier
about the server client ID.

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:31.150
I know it sounds like an
oxymoron, a server client.

00:33:31.150 --> 00:33:35.340
But it's the client ID from
your server to Google servers.

00:33:35.340 --> 00:33:37.610
So you set the
audience with that ID.

00:33:37.610 --> 00:33:38.960
And then you set the issuer.

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:41.350
And the issuers is just
accounts.google.com.

00:33:41.350 --> 00:33:43.100
And then you build this thing.

00:33:43.100 --> 00:33:44.750
And then after you
build this thing,

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:47.650
you can then just verify
your token by calling verify,

00:33:47.650 --> 00:33:51.090
or .verify, that actual
string that was posted up.

00:33:51.090 --> 00:33:53.290
And if that comes
back as not null,

00:33:53.290 --> 00:33:57.027
then this token has a
payload associated with it.

00:33:57.027 --> 00:33:59.110
All the things in orange
on the slide, by the way,

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:00.370
are part of the API.

00:34:00.370 --> 00:34:03.189
So the payloads that you
create from that ID token

00:34:03.189 --> 00:34:04.980
has something, for
example, a method in it,

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:06.030
which is the getSubject.

00:34:06.030 --> 00:34:07.940
And that just gives
you the user ID.

00:34:07.940 --> 00:34:11.320
So if you think about the
flow, the user on your device

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:12.610
tries to sign in.

00:34:12.610 --> 00:34:16.489
When they sign in, Google
issue a token to your device.

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:19.710
Your device then gets that token
and posts it to your server.

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:23.000
Your server gets that token
and posts it back to Google.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.480
Google then verify that
token, and come back and say,

00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:28.070
this is the user ID
associated with that token.

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:32.420
So you have the complete flow
from your device to your server

00:34:32.420 --> 00:34:34.774
securely for your
actual end user.

00:34:34.774 --> 00:34:36.690
So then if you're building,
for example, a dog

00:34:36.690 --> 00:34:38.150
walker application,
and you don't

00:34:38.150 --> 00:34:40.832
want a nefarious third
party to access data

00:34:40.832 --> 00:34:42.790
such as the breed of your
dog, or your address,

00:34:42.790 --> 00:34:45.130
or where you live, this is
a great way of doing that.

00:34:45.130 --> 00:34:46.840
So all of this data
that's in flight

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:48.271
is much more secure
than if it was

00:34:48.271 --> 00:34:50.020
just an e-mail being
passed to your server

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:52.712
to identify the end user.

00:34:52.712 --> 00:34:54.170
So that's really
part of the value.

00:34:54.170 --> 00:34:56.489
And that's what Sign-In
with Google is all about.

00:34:56.489 --> 00:34:59.330
And that's why we're working
